00:02:26.895 --> 00:02:29.360
I am, too.

00:02:29.360 --> 00:02:31.040
So I hear all
great presentations

00:02:31.040 --> 00:02:32.000
start with a story.

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:34.090
That's what people tell me.

00:02:34.090 --> 00:02:35.930
So that's what I'm
going to start with.

00:02:35.930 --> 00:02:38.070
So this is a picture.

00:02:38.070 --> 00:02:40.190
My son Brody is the
one in the hoodie.

00:02:40.190 --> 00:02:40.780
He's 11.

00:02:40.780 --> 00:02:43.160
This picture wasn't
taken that long ago.

00:02:43.160 --> 00:02:46.970
And he had a few
friends at our house.

00:02:46.970 --> 00:02:49.220
And one of the boys,
one of the other boys,

00:02:49.220 --> 00:02:54.410
started talking about a tragedy
that happened in his family

00:02:54.410 --> 00:02:55.950
many, many years ago.

00:02:55.950 --> 00:02:58.700
But it was a pretty
intense tragedy.

00:02:58.700 --> 00:03:03.170
And the other two boys listened
intently-- really listened.

00:03:03.170 --> 00:03:05.280
They were asking some questions.

00:03:05.280 --> 00:03:08.890
And there was a real gravitas to
what was going on in the room.

00:03:08.890 --> 00:03:11.030
And I was just in
the kitchen kind

00:03:11.030 --> 00:03:14.720
of hanging back, just
observing and watching

00:03:14.720 --> 00:03:16.760
and kind of taking it all in.

00:03:16.760 --> 00:03:20.490
And all at once, Brody,
my little guy, said,

00:03:20.490 --> 00:03:22.370
I know what we need to do.

00:03:22.370 --> 00:03:25.550
We need to have a
compassion circle.

00:03:25.550 --> 00:03:28.304
And so he took them, and
one of the kids said,

00:03:28.304 --> 00:03:29.720
well, I've never
done this before.

00:03:29.720 --> 00:03:31.094
Brody said, don't
worry about it.

00:03:31.094 --> 00:03:33.554
I'll tell you what to do.

00:03:33.554 --> 00:03:34.790
He knows the deal.

00:03:34.790 --> 00:03:35.750
I'm feeling very proud.

00:03:35.750 --> 00:03:38.360
Now, every parent-- I'm going
to tell you these two stories

00:03:38.360 --> 00:03:39.920
about my kids--

00:03:39.920 --> 00:03:41.780
these are like the best ones.

00:03:41.780 --> 00:03:44.330
Just so you know, this
isn't like life every day.

00:03:44.330 --> 00:03:47.690
Let's make that clear right now.

00:03:47.690 --> 00:03:49.760
But this was a good one.

00:03:49.760 --> 00:03:52.730
So he walked them
through all sharing

00:03:52.730 --> 00:03:57.770
about what was just said,
and sending good wishes

00:03:57.770 --> 00:03:59.930
to this past place.

00:03:59.930 --> 00:04:02.810
And they were in the circle
for a couple of minutes,

00:04:02.810 --> 00:04:05.300
and then they went
on their evening.

00:04:05.300 --> 00:04:06.680
They unlocked hands.

00:04:06.680 --> 00:04:09.980
And they were going on a
night walk with flashlights,

00:04:09.980 --> 00:04:12.800
and off they went.

00:04:12.800 --> 00:04:15.020
But I was, of
course, as the mom,

00:04:15.020 --> 00:04:18.529
I mean I was a little teary
eyed and a little stunned.

00:04:18.529 --> 00:04:21.290
I mean, he's done things
similar to this, but not quite.

00:04:21.290 --> 00:04:24.080
You know, he knew what to do.

00:04:24.080 --> 00:04:27.950
In that moment, he'd
had the practices in him

00:04:27.950 --> 00:04:30.020
enough through me--
and I didn't teach him

00:04:30.020 --> 00:04:32.480
to go do compassion circles.

00:04:32.480 --> 00:04:39.390
He just had the sense to pause
and to stop and to check in.

00:04:39.390 --> 00:04:41.200
So one more story.

00:04:41.200 --> 00:04:42.360
This is my son Tyler.

00:04:42.360 --> 00:04:45.330
Again, not taken that long ago.

00:04:45.330 --> 00:04:47.040
And he's an athlete.

00:04:47.040 --> 00:04:48.580
He is extremely active.

00:04:48.580 --> 00:04:50.010
He has two speeds--

00:04:50.010 --> 00:04:52.440
full speed and no speed.

00:04:52.440 --> 00:04:56.580
And he's had a lot of injuries
in his very short life.

00:04:56.580 --> 00:05:00.120
And he was subbing
in a basketball game

00:05:00.120 --> 00:05:01.170
with a friend of his.

00:05:01.170 --> 00:05:02.730
He wasn't even supposed
to be playing in the game.

00:05:02.730 --> 00:05:04.440
He actually was
there just to watch.

00:05:04.440 --> 00:05:07.107
And they were short a player,
because it was winter break,

00:05:07.107 --> 00:05:08.940
and so they asked him
to play, which he did.

00:05:08.940 --> 00:05:09.773
I wasn't even there.

00:05:09.773 --> 00:05:12.090
I had no idea he was
playing basketball.

00:05:12.090 --> 00:05:16.620
And I get a phone call that he
had gotten pushed and shoved

00:05:16.620 --> 00:05:19.470
and fell, and his
best friend kicked

00:05:19.470 --> 00:05:24.450
him, broke his collarbone
trying to keep the ball in.

00:05:24.450 --> 00:05:25.830
40 seconds left to the game.

00:05:25.830 --> 00:05:27.870
So he was in an
incredible amount of pain.

00:05:27.870 --> 00:05:29.820
The paramedics came and got him.

00:05:29.820 --> 00:05:32.160
We ended up in the
hospital, of course.

00:05:32.160 --> 00:05:33.870
On one side of us
in the hospital

00:05:33.870 --> 00:05:37.140
was a meth addict
who's had an infection,

00:05:37.140 --> 00:05:41.010
and was not very present.

00:05:41.010 --> 00:05:43.710
And on the other side was a
man who'd been brought in--

00:05:43.710 --> 00:05:46.360
and very rare, apparently,
I found out later,

00:05:46.360 --> 00:05:47.520
in the emergency room.

00:05:47.520 --> 00:05:50.460
The trauma unit was there
trying to keep him alive,

00:05:50.460 --> 00:05:53.940
and he did not stay
alive, right next to us.

00:05:53.940 --> 00:05:56.580
So Tyler experienced that.

00:05:56.580 --> 00:05:58.950
And we kind of
paused together when

00:05:58.950 --> 00:06:02.549
we realized this man had passed,
and sent him good wishes,

00:06:02.549 --> 00:06:03.840
and put our hands on his heart.

00:06:03.840 --> 00:06:05.470
He was in an incredible
amount of pain.

00:06:05.470 --> 00:06:09.870
Apparently the collarbone
is only second to the spine

00:06:09.870 --> 00:06:11.400
to break.

00:06:11.400 --> 00:06:12.870
So we got home.

00:06:12.870 --> 00:06:15.570
Very difficult to get him
in the car, to get him home,

00:06:15.570 --> 00:06:17.850
to get him slowly
down on the bed.

00:06:17.850 --> 00:06:19.740
I had to help him
go to the bathroom.

00:06:19.740 --> 00:06:22.860
I mean, he couldn't do
anything for himself.

00:06:22.860 --> 00:06:27.810
And when I finally got him
settled, here's the moment.

00:06:27.810 --> 00:06:31.980
He's like, mom, I'm getting
to have the experience of what

00:06:31.980 --> 00:06:35.280
it's like to be disabled.

00:06:35.280 --> 00:06:36.180
I said, you are.

00:06:36.180 --> 00:06:36.680
You are.

00:06:36.680 --> 00:06:38.263
And he said, and
you're getting to see

00:06:38.263 --> 00:06:43.020
what it's like to take
care of a disabled child.

00:06:43.020 --> 00:06:46.310
I said, you're right, I am.

00:06:46.310 --> 00:06:48.920
And then-- I'll try
not to get weepy.

00:06:48.920 --> 00:06:50.840
He said, you know,
I'm going to have

00:06:50.840 --> 00:06:56.560
a lot more compassion for
disabled people moving forward.

00:06:56.560 --> 00:06:59.620
And again, you
know, I'm stunned.

00:06:59.620 --> 00:07:02.537
And I got teary eyed with him.

00:07:02.537 --> 00:07:03.870
And he said, why are you crying?

00:07:03.870 --> 00:07:04.369
Of course.

00:07:04.369 --> 00:07:06.810
He's 14.

00:07:06.810 --> 00:07:08.340
Why are you crying?

00:07:08.340 --> 00:07:12.940
And I tried to explain to him
in the best language I could

00:07:12.940 --> 00:07:18.220
how remarkable it was that in
the greatest pain of his life,

00:07:18.220 --> 00:07:20.680
for sure-- he's never
been in this kind of pain.

00:07:20.680 --> 00:07:23.530
The darkest, one of the
darkest moments of his life--

00:07:23.530 --> 00:07:27.370
he knows he's not going to
play sports for a few months--

00:07:27.370 --> 00:07:33.300
that you were able to find
the learning and the beauty

00:07:33.300 --> 00:07:36.680
in this mess that you're in.

00:07:36.680 --> 00:07:42.020
And I told him, most adults
don't get there in a lifetime,

00:07:42.020 --> 00:07:43.210
in a lifetime--

00:07:43.210 --> 00:07:47.090
to be in that space and
to see the potential,

00:07:47.090 --> 00:07:48.440
and to see the positivity.

00:07:52.810 --> 00:07:58.180
So I love this image,
because we learn the most,

00:07:58.180 --> 00:08:00.040
and we have the
most opportunities

00:08:00.040 --> 00:08:03.370
to awaken and to
find our mindfulness

00:08:03.370 --> 00:08:08.590
and to find our compassion
in the most difficult parts

00:08:08.590 --> 00:08:09.870
of our lives--

00:08:09.870 --> 00:08:11.575
in the cracks, in the darkness.

00:08:14.960 --> 00:08:16.550
This is where the
opportunity is.

00:08:16.550 --> 00:08:19.250
But we don't like that.

00:08:19.250 --> 00:08:23.180
When things go wrong,
we want to push it away.

00:08:23.180 --> 00:08:25.010
We want to push
away the unpleasant,

00:08:25.010 --> 00:08:27.590
and we want to hang
on to the pleasant.

00:08:27.590 --> 00:08:28.620
And that's normal.

00:08:28.620 --> 00:08:31.170
That's what we do
as human beings.

00:08:31.170 --> 00:08:33.080
And this is where these
beautiful practices

00:08:33.080 --> 00:08:35.059
that I guess, I'm
assuming I'm preaching

00:08:35.059 --> 00:08:38.690
to the choir in this room
and on the live stream,

00:08:38.690 --> 00:08:42.809
that mindfulness and
compassion is important to you.

00:08:42.809 --> 00:08:45.930
And this is what these
practices offer us,

00:08:45.930 --> 00:08:50.160
that we can start to hold the
pleasant and the unpleasant,

00:08:50.160 --> 00:08:53.880
the dark and the light,
the beauty and the yuck

00:08:53.880 --> 00:08:59.910
in our lives, at the same time,
and be able to see clearly.

00:08:59.910 --> 00:09:02.730
I love this quote, I think
goes so well with what I just

00:09:02.730 --> 00:09:04.410
shared, by Rumi.

00:09:04.410 --> 00:09:05.850
"Don't turn away.

00:09:05.850 --> 00:09:09.070
Keep your gaze on
the bandaged places.

00:09:09.070 --> 00:09:12.160
That's where the
light enters you."

00:09:12.160 --> 00:09:15.600
And that's really just what
happened to my son Tyler

00:09:15.600 --> 00:09:18.180
and to my son Brody
during the time

00:09:18.180 --> 00:09:21.250
that they were
sitting in darkness.

00:09:21.250 --> 00:09:25.020
And it was in this wounded
place that the light

00:09:25.020 --> 00:09:27.450
entered both of them.

00:09:27.450 --> 00:09:30.480
And we can all have
those experiences.

00:09:30.480 --> 00:09:32.490
And we probably
all have had them.

00:09:32.490 --> 00:09:34.320
Certainly when you
ask people, what

00:09:34.320 --> 00:09:37.211
is the greatest
learning of your life?

00:09:37.211 --> 00:09:39.210
Tell me about the time
that you learned the most

00:09:39.210 --> 00:09:39.840
about yourself.

00:09:39.840 --> 00:09:42.960
Very few people will point
to something fantastic.

00:09:42.960 --> 00:09:44.850
They weren't at Disney World.

00:09:44.850 --> 00:09:47.580
They weren't out dancing.

00:09:47.580 --> 00:09:50.130
Usually it's something heavy.

00:09:50.130 --> 00:09:53.100
It's a sickness, it's an
illness, it's a death.

00:09:53.100 --> 00:09:55.410
It's one of those
things that brings us

00:09:55.410 --> 00:09:58.412
to those heavier places.

00:09:58.412 --> 00:09:59.870
So I'm not trying
to be depressing.

00:09:59.870 --> 00:10:01.850
We'll lighten up a little bit.

00:10:01.850 --> 00:10:03.860
And I love this quote,
as well, by Rumi.

00:10:03.860 --> 00:10:06.710
"The cure for the
pain, is in the pain."

00:10:06.710 --> 00:10:10.130
So we want to dive in,
we want to go deep,

00:10:10.130 --> 00:10:13.360
we want to be willing
to go in and dive deep.

00:10:13.360 --> 00:10:15.650
In the last 24 hours,
my youngest son,

00:10:15.650 --> 00:10:19.850
Brody, the compassion man,
had a really hard time.

00:10:19.850 --> 00:10:22.100
He has a lot of
learning differences.

00:10:22.100 --> 00:10:23.344
School is a struggle.

00:10:23.344 --> 00:10:25.010
We've changed schools
almost every year.

00:10:25.010 --> 00:10:26.510
He's been having a
really hard time.

00:10:26.510 --> 00:10:30.650
And he had the meltdown
of meltdowns yesterday.

00:10:30.650 --> 00:10:34.880
And it took everything
in me to sit with him

00:10:34.880 --> 00:10:36.860
and find compassion.

00:10:36.860 --> 00:10:39.140
It was really, really hard.

00:10:39.140 --> 00:10:41.840
But I knew the cure for
the pain was in the pain.

00:10:41.840 --> 00:10:46.370
And I knew my job was to sit
with him, just like I did year

00:10:46.370 --> 00:10:47.810
after year when
he was very young.

00:10:47.810 --> 00:10:51.020
We didn't understand why, always
having a temper tantrum, always

00:10:51.020 --> 00:10:51.726
on the floor.

00:10:51.726 --> 00:10:53.225
We didn't understand,
we didn't know

00:10:53.225 --> 00:10:55.610
at that time what was going on.

00:10:55.610 --> 00:10:56.930
And he's a wonderful kid.

00:10:56.930 --> 00:11:02.480
Super creative, non-linear, but
a lot of barriers to learning.

00:11:02.480 --> 00:11:05.210
And when he was younger,
that was my practice,

00:11:05.210 --> 00:11:07.970
to sit with him as the
temper tantrum went on,

00:11:07.970 --> 00:11:09.860
and to sit with him
and to let him know,

00:11:09.860 --> 00:11:12.339
I will hold this with you.

00:11:12.339 --> 00:11:14.380
And that was what I tried
to offer him yesterday,

00:11:14.380 --> 00:11:16.796
and that was what my husband
tried to offer him yesterday.

00:11:16.796 --> 00:11:18.000
We will hold this with you.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:23.070
We are willing to sit in this
pain with you, this messiness,

00:11:23.070 --> 00:11:24.660
and hold this with you.

00:11:24.660 --> 00:11:26.780
And there's light
in here, as well,

00:11:26.780 --> 00:11:29.100
that you can't see right now.

00:11:29.100 --> 00:11:31.600
Mindful parenting
in a messy world--

00:11:31.600 --> 00:11:34.500
that's why I named
the book what I did.

00:11:34.500 --> 00:11:36.716
So what gets in our way?

00:11:36.716 --> 00:11:37.590
What gets in our way?

00:11:37.590 --> 00:11:40.410
This tree is on the ground.

00:11:40.410 --> 00:11:44.610
What we want is to be that
redwood tree standing tall.

00:11:44.610 --> 00:11:47.250
You've probably heard
that image of the redwood.

00:11:47.250 --> 00:11:50.940
The wind comes, the storm
comes, it kind of blows over,

00:11:50.940 --> 00:11:52.350
but then it comes back up.

00:11:52.350 --> 00:11:54.147
And I like to add that--

00:11:54.147 --> 00:11:55.980
I didn't always know
this, but redwood trees

00:11:55.980 --> 00:12:00.240
have very not deep roots,
very shallow roots.

00:12:00.240 --> 00:12:03.630
But they're connected to
community around each other.

00:12:03.630 --> 00:12:05.550
They're connected to
family around each other.

00:12:05.550 --> 00:12:08.010
And I think that's a beautiful
metaphor for the parenting

00:12:08.010 --> 00:12:12.330
journey, is that this is what
we do at home as a family,

00:12:12.330 --> 00:12:15.180
no matter what that
family looks like.

00:12:15.180 --> 00:12:18.810
We have shallow roots that
we're all hanging on to,

00:12:18.810 --> 00:12:20.910
sometimes for dear life.

00:12:20.910 --> 00:12:23.610
But we're all hanging on
to those roots together.

00:12:23.610 --> 00:12:28.810
And that was what we were trying
to be with my son yesterday.

00:12:28.810 --> 00:12:33.580
And this is what I think
is the big aha for me.

00:12:33.580 --> 00:12:36.230
I've been noodling on this
statement for a while,

00:12:36.230 --> 00:12:37.090
"Everything is fine.

00:12:37.090 --> 00:12:38.530
Until it isn't.

00:12:38.530 --> 00:12:40.090
And then it is again."

00:12:40.090 --> 00:12:42.670
And I actually wrote
a blog post about it

00:12:42.670 --> 00:12:47.890
not too long ago when I was
traveling over the holidays.

00:12:47.890 --> 00:12:51.680
And this is what
gets in our way.

00:12:51.680 --> 00:12:54.270
Because everything is fine, and
then it isn't, and then it is.

00:12:54.270 --> 00:12:55.750
And we don't like
it when it's not.

00:12:55.750 --> 00:12:59.402
When it's not, we believe
something's wrong.

00:12:59.402 --> 00:13:01.110
And if we're always
believing something's

00:13:01.110 --> 00:13:05.940
wrong when it's
not OK, then we're

00:13:05.940 --> 00:13:08.580
never going to have those
opportunities to find

00:13:08.580 --> 00:13:11.520
the light in the crack.

00:13:11.520 --> 00:13:14.010
We need to be OK
with our not OK-ness.

00:13:14.010 --> 00:13:16.800
Because let's face it--
how many parents in here?

00:13:16.800 --> 00:13:17.890
Parents, raise your hands.

00:13:17.890 --> 00:13:21.210
So pretty much everybody,
almost everyone.

00:13:21.210 --> 00:13:23.350
Parenting is hard.

00:13:23.350 --> 00:13:24.750
It's not easy.

00:13:24.750 --> 00:13:27.330
I've been focused
on these practices

00:13:27.330 --> 00:13:30.090
and working on myself and
doing inquiry and sitting

00:13:30.090 --> 00:13:35.510
on my cushion and going
through trainings and teaching,

00:13:35.510 --> 00:13:37.320
and I still have a hard time.

00:13:37.320 --> 00:13:38.380
Parenting is hard.

00:13:38.380 --> 00:13:39.160
It's not easy.

00:13:39.160 --> 00:13:40.990
It's not meant to be easy.

00:13:40.990 --> 00:13:43.600
And we're meant to fall,
and then get back up.

00:13:46.480 --> 00:13:48.760
So here is what happens.

00:13:48.760 --> 00:13:52.240
The movies-- we
all have this movie

00:13:52.240 --> 00:13:54.850
in our mind of how things
are supposed to be.

00:13:54.850 --> 00:13:56.560
We've all had this
experience, right?

00:13:56.560 --> 00:13:59.830
We're going to go someplace
special with our family,

00:13:59.830 --> 00:14:01.480
and we've been
thinking about it,

00:14:01.480 --> 00:14:03.250
and we have it in
our mind in the movie

00:14:03.250 --> 00:14:04.690
and what it's going to be like.

00:14:04.690 --> 00:14:07.540
And then we get
there, and nothing

00:14:07.540 --> 00:14:09.400
goes the way we planned.

00:14:09.400 --> 00:14:12.322
And the movie's not
matching reality.

00:14:12.322 --> 00:14:13.030
And what happens?

00:14:15.550 --> 00:14:18.100
We go downhill.

00:14:18.100 --> 00:14:22.630
We'll sabotage-- we'll
sabotage our experience.

00:14:22.630 --> 00:14:25.260
So what mindfulness
gives us, and I'm

00:14:25.260 --> 00:14:30.030
sure you've had this
experience, is to see the movie.

00:14:30.030 --> 00:14:31.330
We see the movie playing.

00:14:31.330 --> 00:14:35.940
Yesterday, all day with
my son, I saw the movie.

00:14:35.940 --> 00:14:37.750
It's not supposed
to be this hard.

00:14:37.750 --> 00:14:39.041
That's what I'm telling myself.

00:14:39.041 --> 00:14:42.030
I'm seeing the
images of him calm

00:14:42.030 --> 00:14:44.640
and going to school
every day and not calling

00:14:44.640 --> 00:14:46.830
and the nurse not calling me.

00:14:46.830 --> 00:14:52.360
And I have this movie of what
it's supposed to be like.

00:14:52.360 --> 00:14:54.946
But I don't buy it.

00:14:54.946 --> 00:14:55.570
I don't buy it.

00:14:55.570 --> 00:14:58.740
And when we have our
mindfulness, we don't buy it.

00:14:58.740 --> 00:15:01.060
And I love the image
of mindfulness.

00:15:01.060 --> 00:15:05.890
This is something that happens,
something that we consider

00:15:05.890 --> 00:15:08.090
is not good in some way.

00:15:08.090 --> 00:15:10.270
And then there's our reaction.

00:15:10.270 --> 00:15:12.250
And when we don't
have our mindfulness,

00:15:12.250 --> 00:15:14.470
these two things are
right next to each other.

00:15:14.470 --> 00:15:18.640
There is the bad thing, and
then there's our reaction.

00:15:18.640 --> 00:15:20.510
And when we have
our mindfulness,

00:15:20.510 --> 00:15:24.640
and we have our compassion,
this space opens up.

00:15:24.640 --> 00:15:28.210
And we've all had that
experience of, oh, this time,

00:15:28.210 --> 00:15:30.250
there was a little bit of space.

00:15:30.250 --> 00:15:32.740
And I was able to make
a different choice,

00:15:32.740 --> 00:15:34.180
and make a different decision.

00:15:34.180 --> 00:15:38.500
And in family life, we want
to be watching those movies.

00:15:38.500 --> 00:15:39.670
What is the story?

00:15:39.670 --> 00:15:42.830
What is the story that you tell
yourself about your children?

00:15:42.830 --> 00:15:44.650
What's the story that
you tell yourself

00:15:44.650 --> 00:15:47.500
about your relationship
to your children?

00:15:47.500 --> 00:15:49.700
And does it match?

00:15:49.700 --> 00:15:50.690
It's an exploration.

00:15:50.690 --> 00:15:52.430
There's no one answer.

00:15:52.430 --> 00:15:54.800
But I encourage you to journal.

00:15:54.800 --> 00:15:56.300
Journal on those stories.

00:15:56.300 --> 00:15:57.170
What are they?

00:15:57.170 --> 00:16:00.170
What are the stories that you
hold true about your family?

00:16:00.170 --> 00:16:02.120
I have one about my
two boys, that they're

00:16:02.120 --> 00:16:05.540
supposed to be super close.

00:16:05.540 --> 00:16:07.400
Aren't brothers supposed
to be super close?

00:16:07.400 --> 00:16:10.550
My husband and I had two
kids to live vicariously

00:16:10.550 --> 00:16:13.280
through siblings, because
we're both only children.

00:16:13.280 --> 00:16:15.170
So we wanted to see
what it was like.

00:16:15.170 --> 00:16:18.970
That was our first mistake, that
we had this movie in our mind,

00:16:18.970 --> 00:16:21.050
oh, we get to see siblings.

00:16:21.050 --> 00:16:24.620
Well, they couldn't be any
more opposite in the world,

00:16:24.620 --> 00:16:28.040
and they don't like each
other that much, is the truth.

00:16:28.040 --> 00:16:29.420
You know, they have moments.

00:16:29.420 --> 00:16:32.810
And so I've learned to just
take those moments for what they

00:16:32.810 --> 00:16:37.100
are, and just keep planting
those seeds of love

00:16:37.100 --> 00:16:39.640
and connection between
the two of them.

00:16:39.640 --> 00:16:43.650
But the movie is not working
out the way that I planned.

00:16:43.650 --> 00:16:49.220
And I work on being OK
with that not being OK.

00:16:49.220 --> 00:16:50.610
Because it's hard.

00:16:50.610 --> 00:16:51.110
It's hard.

00:16:53.760 --> 00:16:56.980
So these are all
pictures of my family,

00:16:56.980 --> 00:17:01.874
and we're happy, and were
smiling, and we're connected.

00:17:01.874 --> 00:17:03.415
So what do you
think-- what could you

00:17:03.415 --> 00:17:06.040
imagine all of these
pictures have in common?

00:17:06.040 --> 00:17:09.579
We're on vacation.

00:17:09.579 --> 00:17:13.780
And the other thing that all
these pictures have in common

00:17:13.780 --> 00:17:16.720
is that there was
fighting beforehand--

00:17:16.720 --> 00:17:19.300
not long before, just
a little while before.

00:17:19.300 --> 00:17:21.707
There was arguing
and bickering and--

00:17:21.707 --> 00:17:22.990
ugh.

00:17:22.990 --> 00:17:26.079
The day from the beach
photo that you're seeing,

00:17:26.079 --> 00:17:28.960
that full day was what I
wrote this blog post about.

00:17:28.960 --> 00:17:32.500
And things happened, like in the
morning, I woke up, and I sat,

00:17:32.500 --> 00:17:35.020
I did my little meditation,
we were on the water.

00:17:35.020 --> 00:17:37.360
I'm like, oh, this is
such a good moment.

00:17:37.360 --> 00:17:39.320
I love this moment.

00:17:39.320 --> 00:17:43.750
And then my older son, who's
an adolescent now, woke up

00:17:43.750 --> 00:17:45.610
and kind of came into
the room like, ugh.

00:17:45.610 --> 00:17:48.160
You know, it was kind
of a grunt happened.

00:17:48.160 --> 00:17:51.010
And I was like, mm, that's
not such a good moment.

00:17:51.010 --> 00:17:53.390
I would have preferred
that had been different.

00:17:53.390 --> 00:17:55.180
And then my son,
my two kids were

00:17:55.180 --> 00:17:57.490
sitting on the couch
reading, not engaged,

00:17:57.490 --> 00:17:58.930
but somewhat close
to each other,

00:17:58.930 --> 00:18:00.138
both reading very peacefully.

00:18:00.138 --> 00:18:02.880
And I'm like, oh,
see, this is so nice.

00:18:02.880 --> 00:18:04.900
This is a nice moment.

00:18:04.900 --> 00:18:06.982
And then it was time
to leave, and there

00:18:06.982 --> 00:18:09.190
was an argument of who was
going to sit in the front,

00:18:09.190 --> 00:18:11.300
and so that big
argument happened.

00:18:11.300 --> 00:18:12.550
And I didn't like that moment.

00:18:12.550 --> 00:18:13.810
I'm like, ugh, not OK.

00:18:13.810 --> 00:18:15.190
This is not OK.

00:18:15.190 --> 00:18:19.000
And then we're on the way there,
and '90s hip hop is playing,

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:20.770
and we're all
singing in the car.

00:18:20.770 --> 00:18:23.070
I'm like, oh, see, we're
a nice, normal family.

00:18:23.070 --> 00:18:27.580
Look at us having a good
time listening to music.

00:18:27.580 --> 00:18:29.140
And then it's time
to stop somewhere

00:18:29.140 --> 00:18:31.870
to get some food before
we go where we're going,

00:18:31.870 --> 00:18:33.600
and no one can
agree on the food,

00:18:33.600 --> 00:18:35.370
and everyone's got
food allergies anyway,

00:18:35.370 --> 00:18:37.110
and my husband storms out.

00:18:37.110 --> 00:18:39.220
We're at three
cafes to get food.

00:18:39.220 --> 00:18:40.990
I'm like, it's just lunch.

00:18:40.990 --> 00:18:43.360
Why does it have
to be this hard?

00:18:43.360 --> 00:18:48.110
And then there we are on
the beach not long after.

00:18:48.110 --> 00:18:50.560
But that's the way of it, right?

00:18:50.560 --> 00:18:52.120
That is the way of it.

00:18:52.120 --> 00:18:53.770
That's just parenting.

00:18:53.770 --> 00:18:55.660
That's just family life.

00:18:55.660 --> 00:19:01.720
And it's very easy, and I know
you have all thought, god,

00:19:01.720 --> 00:19:04.390
this is a really rough day.

00:19:04.390 --> 00:19:06.280
This is a really rough day.

00:19:06.280 --> 00:19:09.346
But if we look at the moments,
like the moment by moment

00:19:09.346 --> 00:19:10.720
by moment, it's
kind of like when

00:19:10.720 --> 00:19:12.490
you're sitting in meditation.

00:19:12.490 --> 00:19:16.480
And sometimes it's peaceful, and
you can kind of ease into it.

00:19:16.480 --> 00:19:19.150
And then the mind goes
wild, and you're just

00:19:19.150 --> 00:19:23.650
kind of trying to figure out
where you're going and hang on.

00:19:23.650 --> 00:19:25.690
And then you kind
of settle again.

00:19:25.690 --> 00:19:28.660
It's up and it's down, and
that's just the way of it.

00:19:31.360 --> 00:19:34.050
So those are the
pictures you didn't see.

00:19:34.050 --> 00:19:38.040
You didn't-- I didn't put
those pictures on Instagram

00:19:38.040 --> 00:19:39.360
or anywhere.

00:19:39.360 --> 00:19:43.410
I didn't talk about
how we were arguing.

00:19:43.410 --> 00:19:46.380
I might tell my friends,
but we don't see that.

00:19:46.380 --> 00:19:49.140
We don't see that out
in social media land.

00:19:49.140 --> 00:19:50.972
We keep that to ourselves.

00:19:53.690 --> 00:19:57.770
So all of these
emotions come through.

00:19:57.770 --> 00:20:01.040
We've got the anger.

00:20:01.040 --> 00:20:02.540
Anger comes.

00:20:02.540 --> 00:20:07.110
And we're not happy, like,
we're not supposed to be angry.

00:20:07.110 --> 00:20:09.270
Anger is not OK.

00:20:09.270 --> 00:20:12.907
And the fear comes, and I
don't want to be afraid.

00:20:12.907 --> 00:20:14.490
Or we don't even
realize we're afraid.

00:20:14.490 --> 00:20:18.210
We're just reacting from afraid.

00:20:18.210 --> 00:20:22.320
And then shame comes, that
mac daddy emotion that

00:20:22.320 --> 00:20:24.510
dysregulates everything else.

00:20:24.510 --> 00:20:28.890
And there's the shame that I
snapped and I raised my voice.

00:20:28.890 --> 00:20:33.030
And what if you knew that,
even after all these practices,

00:20:33.030 --> 00:20:34.770
I still raise my voice.

00:20:34.770 --> 00:20:38.040
I've been trying not
to yell for 10 years.

00:20:38.040 --> 00:20:40.860
And I do it less,
but I still do it.

00:20:40.860 --> 00:20:45.250
And then it happens, and
immediately the shame comes.

00:20:45.250 --> 00:20:46.960
But I have to know it's there.

00:20:46.960 --> 00:20:50.010
I have to be aware of the shame.

00:20:50.010 --> 00:20:50.800
This is the gift.

00:20:50.800 --> 00:20:53.550
There's got to be
a little space.

00:20:53.550 --> 00:20:54.480
So I see the shame.

00:20:54.480 --> 00:20:57.600
And what if you
knew, what if you

00:20:57.600 --> 00:21:00.300
knew how mean my kids
were to each other

00:21:00.300 --> 00:21:04.490
and how angry that
made me sometimes?

00:21:04.490 --> 00:21:06.360
And what if you knew
I was terrified.

00:21:06.360 --> 00:21:08.944
I'm terrified that my kids won't
be friends when they grow up,

00:21:08.944 --> 00:21:11.193
that they're not going to
be close, that they're going

00:21:11.193 --> 00:21:12.450
to have two separate lives.

00:21:12.450 --> 00:21:15.560
That really scares me.

00:21:15.560 --> 00:21:19.640
But what we know is that
"awareness is like the sun.

00:21:19.640 --> 00:21:23.360
When it shines on things,
they are transformed."

00:21:23.360 --> 00:21:25.430
The wise Thich Nhat Hanh.

00:21:25.430 --> 00:21:30.120
And so, just even what I
did right here with you,

00:21:30.120 --> 00:21:34.760
the uber vulnerability, standing
in front of a room of people

00:21:34.760 --> 00:21:35.390
and sharing.

00:21:35.390 --> 00:21:37.640
All those things are true
that I shared with you.

00:21:37.640 --> 00:21:40.200
I'm not making them up.

00:21:40.200 --> 00:21:43.320
When we shine a
light on the shame

00:21:43.320 --> 00:21:50.411
and the fear and the
anger, something happens.

00:21:50.411 --> 00:21:52.160
It's like when we're
sitting in meditation

00:21:52.160 --> 00:21:53.730
and we're thinking,
thinking, thinking,

00:21:53.730 --> 00:21:54.950
and then we notice the thought.

00:21:54.950 --> 00:21:55.450
Right?

00:21:55.450 --> 00:21:56.390
That's our practice.

00:21:56.390 --> 00:21:58.910
We notice the thought,
like the bubble--

00:21:58.910 --> 00:22:00.387
gone.

00:22:00.387 --> 00:22:01.970
We shine the light
of awareness on it.

00:22:04.680 --> 00:22:06.260
And then we feel like this.

00:22:06.260 --> 00:22:07.440
We're like, woo hoo!

00:22:07.440 --> 00:22:09.120
You know, I'm aware.

00:22:09.120 --> 00:22:10.440
I'm awake.

00:22:10.440 --> 00:22:12.660
And we do that moment
by moment by moment.

00:22:12.660 --> 00:22:15.240
And we do it, and we teach
our children to do it.

00:22:15.240 --> 00:22:19.140
And we don't teach them to do
it by telling them how to do it.

00:22:19.140 --> 00:22:21.540
We-- I teach my
children to do that

00:22:21.540 --> 00:22:24.080
by saying out loud
what's going on for me.

00:22:24.080 --> 00:22:26.980
So, say I'm in the
kitchen and everybody

00:22:26.980 --> 00:22:28.890
is having a hard
time, and I'm finding

00:22:28.890 --> 00:22:30.120
myself really irritated.

00:22:30.120 --> 00:22:33.070
I might say, I'm
really irritated.

00:22:33.070 --> 00:22:34.080
Like, I'm noticing.

00:22:34.080 --> 00:22:37.220
My jaw is tight, my stomach
feels a little sick,

00:22:37.220 --> 00:22:39.480
my heart feels a little
tight, my chest area

00:22:39.480 --> 00:22:41.350
feels a little tight.

00:22:41.350 --> 00:22:42.160
I need a break.

00:22:42.160 --> 00:22:45.220
I'm about to say something
I don't want to say.

00:22:45.220 --> 00:22:47.547
So I'm going to go away,
and I'm going to come back.

00:22:47.547 --> 00:22:49.880
I'm going to go away, I'm
going to breathe a little bit,

00:22:49.880 --> 00:22:52.160
I'm going to get a little space,
and I'm going to come back.

00:22:52.160 --> 00:22:53.284
I don't do that every time.

00:22:53.284 --> 00:22:57.290
Sometimes I blow it, and I say
something I wish I hadn't said.

00:22:57.290 --> 00:22:58.890
And then I have to repair.

00:22:58.890 --> 00:23:01.250
But the repair is just as good.

00:23:01.250 --> 00:23:05.330
The repair is just as good
as catching it, sharing it,

00:23:05.330 --> 00:23:07.040
making it explicit.

00:23:07.040 --> 00:23:12.410
If we as parents are practicing
and waking up and becoming more

00:23:12.410 --> 00:23:15.170
conscious, and we're
saying it out loud,

00:23:15.170 --> 00:23:19.700
we're giving them this
experience to voice,

00:23:19.700 --> 00:23:22.440
then they learn how to do it.

00:23:22.440 --> 00:23:25.390
They learn.

00:23:25.390 --> 00:23:27.910
So how, how do we
do this as parents?

00:23:27.910 --> 00:23:31.600
And many of you may
already practice.

00:23:31.600 --> 00:23:32.850
But I have something to offer.

00:23:32.850 --> 00:23:34.290
So here we are, right?

00:23:34.290 --> 00:23:36.930
This is kind of what our
lives often look like.

00:23:36.930 --> 00:23:39.650
We're falling
asleep at our desk.

00:23:39.650 --> 00:23:41.512
We're just spent.

00:23:41.512 --> 00:23:42.470
We're completely spent.

00:23:42.470 --> 00:23:45.860
We're trying to get bills paid,
we're trying to get work done,

00:23:45.860 --> 00:23:48.150
and it's just hard.

00:23:48.150 --> 00:23:49.620
It's hard to make it all happen.

00:23:49.620 --> 00:23:50.640
So how do we do it?

00:23:50.640 --> 00:23:54.796
How do we do it in
the course of a day?

00:23:54.796 --> 00:23:56.170
Because this is
how I often feel.

00:23:56.170 --> 00:23:57.480
I'm like, come on.

00:23:57.480 --> 00:23:59.340
Come on, inner peace.

00:23:59.340 --> 00:24:01.750
I don't have all day.

00:24:01.750 --> 00:24:03.687
But we know that's
impossible, right?

00:24:03.687 --> 00:24:05.520
Sometimes I'm like, why
couldn't I have just

00:24:05.520 --> 00:24:07.520
been one of those people
that was born somewhere

00:24:07.520 --> 00:24:11.250
and just live in a cave, and
this just would have happened?

00:24:11.250 --> 00:24:14.000
That's just not-- it's not
the lives we're living, right?

00:24:14.000 --> 00:24:15.600
We-- everyone here
in this room--

00:24:15.600 --> 00:24:17.880
we're all working
parents, and we

00:24:17.880 --> 00:24:22.210
have to weave in to what
we're already doing.

00:24:22.210 --> 00:24:23.430
And this is good news.

00:24:23.430 --> 00:24:26.650
"To experience peace does not
mean that your life is always

00:24:26.650 --> 00:24:27.670
blissful.

00:24:27.670 --> 00:24:29.800
It means that you are
capable of tapping

00:24:29.800 --> 00:24:34.450
into a blissful state of
mind, amidst the normal chaos

00:24:34.450 --> 00:24:36.040
of a hectic life."

00:24:36.040 --> 00:24:39.010
And Jill Bolte Taylor wrote
the book "Stroke of Genius."

00:24:39.010 --> 00:24:41.750
If you've never read that,
it's a wonderful book.

00:24:41.750 --> 00:24:42.760
And I love this quote.

00:24:42.760 --> 00:24:45.710
I'm like, oh, whew.

00:24:45.710 --> 00:24:48.160
You know, we just have to
be able to tap into it,

00:24:48.160 --> 00:24:50.620
and just touch, touch, touch.

00:24:50.620 --> 00:24:52.120
We can have hard days.

00:24:52.120 --> 00:24:53.080
We will have hard days.

00:24:53.080 --> 00:24:54.250
I don't think you
could be a parent

00:24:54.250 --> 00:24:56.916
and not have a hard day, whether
you have one, or two, or three.

00:24:59.390 --> 00:25:01.550
So we can play.

00:25:01.550 --> 00:25:03.980
I love these images,
because for me they all

00:25:03.980 --> 00:25:08.280
point to things that
I try to do in my day.

00:25:08.280 --> 00:25:10.229
I took on a practice
not long ago.

00:25:10.229 --> 00:25:12.020
How many times have we
heard our kids like,

00:25:12.020 --> 00:25:13.070
will you play with me?

00:25:13.070 --> 00:25:14.270
Will you play with me?

00:25:14.270 --> 00:25:15.960
And what's often the answer?

00:25:15.960 --> 00:25:16.480
I can't.

00:25:16.480 --> 00:25:17.770
Oh, I'm busy.

00:25:17.770 --> 00:25:19.100
Or, I'm making dinner.

00:25:19.100 --> 00:25:21.290
And I was hearing that.

00:25:21.290 --> 00:25:23.840
My mindfulness practice helped
me hear, like, oh my gosh,

00:25:23.840 --> 00:25:26.070
I say that so many times.

00:25:26.070 --> 00:25:30.210
And so I committed to saying
yes for one week, just

00:25:30.210 --> 00:25:31.380
to see how it would go--

00:25:31.380 --> 00:25:32.250
every time.

00:25:32.250 --> 00:25:34.280
Now, this was not
when they were three,

00:25:34.280 --> 00:25:36.130
so that might be a
little different.

00:25:36.130 --> 00:25:38.170
So you might have to say,
like, I'll give myself

00:25:38.170 --> 00:25:40.217
10 times or something.

00:25:40.217 --> 00:25:42.050
This happened when they
were a little older.

00:25:42.050 --> 00:25:44.010
So it wasn't happening
like 10 times a day.

00:25:46.720 --> 00:25:48.150
But I said yes.

00:25:48.150 --> 00:25:49.770
I started saying yes.

00:25:49.770 --> 00:25:53.730
And it was the best
little research study

00:25:53.730 --> 00:25:55.950
I ever did inside of my family.

00:25:55.950 --> 00:25:58.380
We had the sweetest week.

00:25:58.380 --> 00:25:59.235
So I kept it going.

00:25:59.235 --> 00:26:00.360
And I can't always say yes.

00:26:00.360 --> 00:26:02.190
Sometimes I have to say no.

00:26:02.190 --> 00:26:05.460
But I've learned to say
yes more than I say no.

00:26:05.460 --> 00:26:07.140
Yes, I'll jump on
the trampoline.

00:26:07.140 --> 00:26:10.240
I mean, jumping on the
trampoline's super fun.

00:26:10.240 --> 00:26:13.010
There are some really fun games
you can play on the trampoline.

00:26:13.010 --> 00:26:15.690
You know, yes to the card game.

00:26:15.690 --> 00:26:17.550
Yes to the sword fight.

00:26:17.550 --> 00:26:19.660
Yes.

00:26:19.660 --> 00:26:23.050
And it might be that we're
just walking down a busy road.

00:26:23.050 --> 00:26:24.520
That's a great
time to practice--

00:26:24.520 --> 00:26:27.970
walking from here to your next
meeting, or back to your desk.

00:26:27.970 --> 00:26:30.280
What if it was just
a mindful walk.

00:26:30.280 --> 00:26:33.610
What if you were just really
paying attention to your feet

00:26:33.610 --> 00:26:35.740
hitting the ground,
and that was it.

00:26:35.740 --> 00:26:38.860
Or just following your
breath, or just even

00:26:38.860 --> 00:26:41.860
like feeling your
hands swing from here

00:26:41.860 --> 00:26:44.690
to wherever you're going next.

00:26:44.690 --> 00:26:46.910
And when our kids are
having a hard time,

00:26:46.910 --> 00:26:49.580
can we really just pause?

00:26:49.580 --> 00:26:50.660
Can we just stop?

00:26:50.660 --> 00:26:53.240
Can we listen?

00:26:53.240 --> 00:26:55.120
And dinnertime is
such a good one.

00:26:55.120 --> 00:26:58.200
You know dinnertime-- we
don't eat dinner together

00:26:58.200 --> 00:27:00.540
every night by any stretch
of the imagination,

00:27:00.540 --> 00:27:01.620
although I would love to.

00:27:01.620 --> 00:27:04.350
But it feels almost
impossible at my house.

00:27:04.350 --> 00:27:09.090
But when we do, and we do as
often as we can, we hold hands.

00:27:09.090 --> 00:27:12.030
And we do this little hand
squeeze that goes around.

00:27:12.030 --> 00:27:16.000
And it's this sweet
moment of connection.

00:27:16.000 --> 00:27:20.500
Or we can be thankful
for how the food got

00:27:20.500 --> 00:27:24.430
to us, the farmer
that planted it,

00:27:24.430 --> 00:27:27.556
and the person that tended
it, and the truck driver that

00:27:27.556 --> 00:27:29.680
came and picked it up and
brought it to the grocery

00:27:29.680 --> 00:27:32.230
store, and the grocery
store person who took it out

00:27:32.230 --> 00:27:35.080
of the truck, and the person
who put it so beautifully out

00:27:35.080 --> 00:27:37.500
in the grocery store or
at the farmers market,

00:27:37.500 --> 00:27:41.320
and mom or dad who went and
got it and brought it home

00:27:41.320 --> 00:27:43.570
and cooked it, and wow--

00:27:43.570 --> 00:27:45.340
we can be grateful.

00:27:45.340 --> 00:27:48.459
We have a gratitude
jar in our kitchen.

00:27:48.459 --> 00:27:49.750
It's actually a little too big.

00:27:49.750 --> 00:27:51.610
I need to get a little
bit of a smaller one.

00:27:51.610 --> 00:27:53.290
But it's a big
gratitude jar, and it

00:27:53.290 --> 00:27:54.520
says Gratitude Jar on it.

00:27:54.520 --> 00:27:58.210
And I keep paper and
pen right next to it.

00:27:58.210 --> 00:28:02.290
And we'll just go through
practices of, every morning,

00:28:02.290 --> 00:28:05.290
or at night, or if we have
friends over, just writing

00:28:05.290 --> 00:28:07.690
a gratitude and putting it in--

00:28:07.690 --> 00:28:09.910
that pause, just that moment.

00:28:09.910 --> 00:28:11.960
So we build it into what
we're already doing.

00:28:15.330 --> 00:28:16.730
We pause.

00:28:16.730 --> 00:28:18.780
Just press the pause
button throughout the day.

00:28:21.310 --> 00:28:24.050
And so the dedicated practice
that you're seeing more

00:28:24.050 --> 00:28:25.890
in these images are important.

00:28:25.890 --> 00:28:29.220
And research tells us
that retreat practice

00:28:29.220 --> 00:28:30.720
and regular
dedicated practice is

00:28:30.720 --> 00:28:35.400
very supportive for our
well-being and for our brains.

00:28:35.400 --> 00:28:39.330
And, as parents we all know
that dedicated practice--

00:28:39.330 --> 00:28:42.180
where we stop for 20 minutes,
30 minutes, go away for a day,

00:28:42.180 --> 00:28:43.740
go away for a few days--

00:28:43.740 --> 00:28:45.900
is not always possible.

00:28:45.900 --> 00:28:49.230
When I started practicing
about 10 years ago regularly--

00:28:49.230 --> 00:28:50.970
I was introduced
in college when I

00:28:50.970 --> 00:28:52.410
was having a really hard time.

00:28:52.410 --> 00:28:56.430
I went to a unity church
and sat every Sunday there.

00:28:56.430 --> 00:28:59.670
And so that was my introduction
to guided meditation.

00:28:59.670 --> 00:29:02.460
But I didn't start
practicing regularly

00:29:02.460 --> 00:29:07.210
until I had a four-year-old
and a six-month-old.

00:29:07.210 --> 00:29:09.530
That was when I
entered practice.

00:29:09.530 --> 00:29:13.600
So I had to be really
creative of how I practiced.

00:29:13.600 --> 00:29:15.234
And I remember one
of my teachers--

00:29:15.234 --> 00:29:16.900
I was complaining to
one of my teachers,

00:29:16.900 --> 00:29:18.608
I can never go to my
meditation practice,

00:29:18.608 --> 00:29:20.330
and it just never happens.

00:29:20.330 --> 00:29:21.580
And I was all grumpy about it.

00:29:21.580 --> 00:29:24.127
And she said, well, tell me
a little bit about your day.

00:29:24.127 --> 00:29:25.460
So I'm telling her about my day.

00:29:25.460 --> 00:29:27.000
And I get to the end of the day.

00:29:27.000 --> 00:29:30.710
And I'm like, and they always
make me stay in their room

00:29:30.710 --> 00:29:35.370
at night, and I have to stay
there until they fall asleep.

00:29:35.370 --> 00:29:37.580
And then I'm too
tired to practice.

00:29:37.580 --> 00:29:39.110
And you know what's coming next.

00:29:39.110 --> 00:29:41.455
She's like, why don't you
just sit in their room?

00:29:41.455 --> 00:29:45.020
I was like, huh, why don't
I just sit in their room?

00:29:45.020 --> 00:29:46.880
So I put a cushion
in their room,

00:29:46.880 --> 00:29:49.460
and we made this agreement
that as they were falling

00:29:49.460 --> 00:29:52.602
asleep at night I would stay
in their room, I would sit

00:29:52.602 --> 00:29:53.810
and I would do my meditation.

00:29:53.810 --> 00:29:56.019
I'd cuddle with them first
and do our little rituals,

00:29:56.019 --> 00:29:56.893
and then I would sit.

00:29:56.893 --> 00:29:59.450
And I'd say, I'm not leaving
until way after you're asleep.

00:29:59.450 --> 00:30:01.250
I'm doing my practice in here.

00:30:01.250 --> 00:30:05.190
And I did that for years
when they were really little.

00:30:05.190 --> 00:30:09.050
So what are the things that
you're already doing that you

00:30:09.050 --> 00:30:11.930
can weave integrated practice
that we're talking about--

00:30:11.930 --> 00:30:16.090
walking to the office, or
walking down the street--

00:30:16.090 --> 00:30:17.780
or dedicated practice
that you can even

00:30:17.780 --> 00:30:20.436
do in one of your kid's
rooms, if they're super young

00:30:20.436 --> 00:30:21.060
and let you in.

00:30:21.060 --> 00:30:24.104
If they're teenagers they
might not let you in.

00:30:24.104 --> 00:30:25.520
I'm no longer
allowed in at night.

00:30:29.450 --> 00:30:32.910
We start where we
are-- wherever we are.

00:30:32.910 --> 00:30:35.370
Wherever we are, we can
have a moment of practice.

00:30:35.370 --> 00:30:39.270
And you all saw, as soon as we
came in, we took a few breaths,

00:30:39.270 --> 00:30:40.770
everything shifts.

00:30:40.770 --> 00:30:41.520
Everything shifts.

00:30:41.520 --> 00:30:44.640
No matter how busy we are,
or busy our mind goes,

00:30:44.640 --> 00:30:49.739
just a few breaths
brings us back.

00:30:49.739 --> 00:30:51.280
So I'm just going
to run through some

00:30:51.280 --> 00:30:55.750
of my favorite ways of
weaving it into my day,

00:30:55.750 --> 00:30:58.570
or things I like to share.

00:30:58.570 --> 00:31:00.850
Mornings are so wonderful.

00:31:00.850 --> 00:31:02.650
And you don't have
to get out of bed.

00:31:02.650 --> 00:31:05.110
I've done a lot of practice
with Jon Kabat-Zinn,

00:31:05.110 --> 00:31:09.040
and he always says, lay
there, Savasana pose.

00:31:09.040 --> 00:31:10.954
Just open your eyes so
you're not too sleepy.

00:31:10.954 --> 00:31:13.120
If you can close your eyes
and not fall back asleep,

00:31:13.120 --> 00:31:13.690
that's fine.

00:31:13.690 --> 00:31:15.190
But when you wake
up in the morning,

00:31:15.190 --> 00:31:18.010
just lay there and
follow your breath.

00:31:18.010 --> 00:31:19.187
Do a body scan.

00:31:19.187 --> 00:31:20.770
You don't even have
to get out of bed.

00:31:20.770 --> 00:31:26.500
I will often also get up and
sit on my pillow with my husband

00:31:26.500 --> 00:31:31.030
there, and I'll just sit and
close my eyes until someone

00:31:31.030 --> 00:31:32.320
comes to bother me.

00:31:32.320 --> 00:31:34.330
And I practice not
being annoyed that I got

00:31:34.330 --> 00:31:37.470
interrupted from my meditation.

00:31:37.470 --> 00:31:39.960
My bell didn't go off yet.

00:31:39.960 --> 00:31:41.260
I'm not done.

00:31:41.260 --> 00:31:42.670
Oh, I'm done.

00:31:42.670 --> 00:31:43.930
It's over.

00:31:43.930 --> 00:31:46.030
I'm definitely done.

00:31:46.030 --> 00:31:48.437
The shower.

00:31:48.437 --> 00:31:50.020
I've done a lot of
executive coaching.

00:31:50.020 --> 00:31:52.230
I can't tell you how many
times you've heard this--

00:31:52.230 --> 00:31:55.200
I have the best
ideas in the shower.

00:31:55.200 --> 00:31:57.630
Why do we have the best
ideas in the shower?

00:31:57.630 --> 00:31:59.280
We've paused.

00:31:59.280 --> 00:32:01.620
We're in sensation when
we're in the shower.

00:32:01.620 --> 00:32:03.670
The mind quiets.

00:32:03.670 --> 00:32:05.640
So what if we did
that intentionally

00:32:05.640 --> 00:32:07.650
when we got in the
shower, and we just

00:32:07.650 --> 00:32:11.550
felt the hot water on our body,
and we just allowed ourselves

00:32:11.550 --> 00:32:15.275
to be there in the shower?

00:32:15.275 --> 00:32:16.150
One of my favorites--

00:32:16.150 --> 00:32:18.070
I love my cup of
tea in the morning.

00:32:18.070 --> 00:32:20.200
I'm a big fan of Earl Gray tea.

00:32:20.200 --> 00:32:22.600
And usually it gets pushed
off, and gets pushed off.

00:32:22.600 --> 00:32:23.770
I boil the water,
and my husband's

00:32:23.770 --> 00:32:24.770
like, the water's boiling again.

00:32:24.770 --> 00:32:26.690
I'm like, I know, but I
still haven't made my tea.

00:32:26.690 --> 00:32:29.110
I'm dying to make my tea, but
I keep getting interrupted.

00:32:29.110 --> 00:32:31.300
And then there's that moment.

00:32:31.300 --> 00:32:34.900
To me it's one of the magical
moments of my day, that I stop,

00:32:34.900 --> 00:32:37.330
and I just put my
hands on the cup.

00:32:37.330 --> 00:32:39.730
And I smell it, and
I just give myself

00:32:39.730 --> 00:32:43.540
30 seconds or a minute to just
enjoy the heat of the water.

00:32:46.120 --> 00:32:48.760
I love this image.

00:32:48.760 --> 00:32:51.200
When I saw this
image, I thought, wow,

00:32:51.200 --> 00:32:52.330
what a great practice.

00:32:52.330 --> 00:32:53.710
So I tried it.

00:32:53.710 --> 00:32:56.650
And it sounds a little
hokey, but it works.

00:32:56.650 --> 00:33:03.080
Every time-- for one day I tried
it, and then I continued it.

00:33:03.080 --> 00:33:06.030
Every day, every time I
caught a glimpse of myself

00:33:06.030 --> 00:33:07.990
in the mirror, or
in my computer,

00:33:07.990 --> 00:33:10.170
I would say something
kind to myself.

00:33:10.170 --> 00:33:12.320
I would send myself
some kindness.

00:33:12.320 --> 00:33:15.660
Like, depending on the
day, it might have been,

00:33:15.660 --> 00:33:18.810
you're doing the best you can.

00:33:18.810 --> 00:33:19.680
I love you.

00:33:19.680 --> 00:33:24.520
Whatever it might be, I'd
send myself some kindness.

00:33:24.520 --> 00:33:25.814
And mindful listening.

00:33:25.814 --> 00:33:27.730
I kind of mentioned that
a little bit earlier.

00:33:27.730 --> 00:33:30.580
But if you practice
mindful listening,

00:33:30.580 --> 00:33:33.610
it's just that
stopping and noticing

00:33:33.610 --> 00:33:36.120
any thoughts that are in your
mind when someone's talking.

00:33:36.120 --> 00:33:39.277
Are you trying to respond, or
are you really, really gifting

00:33:39.277 --> 00:33:39.860
your presence?

00:33:39.860 --> 00:33:42.240
And with our children,
particularly any older--

00:33:42.240 --> 00:33:44.310
besides me, teenagers in here?

00:33:44.310 --> 00:33:46.240
A few, a few teenagers.

00:33:46.240 --> 00:33:48.490
Mindful listening, for all
of you that are on your way

00:33:48.490 --> 00:33:51.510
to teenage-hood,
it's so critical.

00:33:51.510 --> 00:33:53.060
In the car-- they
get out of school,

00:33:53.060 --> 00:33:54.430
they get in the car,
what do most of us do,

00:33:54.430 --> 00:33:55.638
from the time they're little?

00:33:55.638 --> 00:33:56.420
How was your day?

00:33:56.420 --> 00:33:57.250
What happened?

00:33:57.250 --> 00:33:58.790
How was your test?

00:33:58.790 --> 00:34:01.450
We start pummeling them
with all these questions,

00:34:01.450 --> 00:34:02.200
and they, what?

00:34:02.200 --> 00:34:04.270
Often, they shut down.

00:34:04.270 --> 00:34:05.220
Even little ones will.

00:34:05.220 --> 00:34:07.720
Sometimes the little ones still
want to tell you everything.

00:34:07.720 --> 00:34:11.560
But certainly as they
get older, that's it.

00:34:11.560 --> 00:34:14.710
So I've learned-- shh.

00:34:14.710 --> 00:34:17.620
I pick them up, and I
just-- shh, nothing.

00:34:17.620 --> 00:34:19.750
Just say, I'm happy to see you.

00:34:19.750 --> 00:34:22.460
I'm so happy to see you.

00:34:22.460 --> 00:34:23.460
That's it.

00:34:23.460 --> 00:34:27.150
And almost always the
conversation will come.

00:34:27.150 --> 00:34:32.750
And it's on his terms, not
my terms, and so it arises.

00:34:32.750 --> 00:34:33.870
The car, use the car.

00:34:33.870 --> 00:34:36.210
And, by the way, when
they come to be teenagers,

00:34:36.210 --> 00:34:37.949
they sit in the back
with their friends.

00:34:37.949 --> 00:34:40.185
And for some reason,
you're not there,

00:34:40.185 --> 00:34:42.884
so you get all kinds
of good information

00:34:42.884 --> 00:34:44.864
that you wouldn't have gotten.

00:34:44.864 --> 00:34:47.620
Like, how do you not know
that I'm sitting right here?

00:34:47.620 --> 00:34:49.806
Yeah.

00:34:49.806 --> 00:34:50.389
It's so great.

00:34:50.389 --> 00:34:51.030
And just-- mm.

00:34:51.030 --> 00:34:55.360
Just shh-- don't say anything.

00:34:55.360 --> 00:34:56.840
And I love this image, too.

00:34:56.840 --> 00:34:59.089
Sitting in the car--
also drop-offs, pickups.

00:34:59.089 --> 00:35:01.130
Anybody have to drop the
kids off or pick them up

00:35:01.130 --> 00:35:02.030
at an activity?

00:35:02.030 --> 00:35:02.690
Anybody?

00:35:02.690 --> 00:35:04.310
Yeah, lots of activities.

00:35:04.310 --> 00:35:08.570
In the car, beautiful place
for dedicated practice.

00:35:08.570 --> 00:35:11.840
I'd drop my kids off to
jujitsu or baseball or wherever

00:35:11.840 --> 00:35:14.540
they were going, and I'd
sit in the car for five, 10,

00:35:14.540 --> 00:35:16.490
15 minutes.

00:35:16.490 --> 00:35:17.720
Or a pick up--

00:35:17.720 --> 00:35:20.030
just sit in the car for
five, 10, 15 minutes.

