00:35:29.775 --> 00:35:32.160
But it is on Simple Habit.

00:35:32.160 --> 00:35:38.060
Headspace-- just put your
ear buds in, sit in silence,

00:35:38.060 --> 00:35:42.734
get a guided meditation,
just sit in the car.

00:35:42.734 --> 00:35:43.234
Oh.

00:35:46.050 --> 00:35:48.340
And the smile, the smiles--

00:35:48.340 --> 00:35:51.760
we can really take in
the smiles, the joy.

00:35:51.760 --> 00:35:56.030
We can bring the
joy in more fully.

00:35:56.030 --> 00:35:58.835
So I really encourage
you all to make a list.

00:35:58.835 --> 00:36:00.520
It doesn't have to be right now.

00:36:00.520 --> 00:36:02.695
But remember to
make a list of what

00:36:02.695 --> 00:36:05.320
you do from the time you wake up
in the morning to the time you

00:36:05.320 --> 00:36:06.130
go to bed at night.

00:36:06.130 --> 00:36:07.755
I'll do this with
parents in workshops.

00:36:07.755 --> 00:36:09.970
And I'm doing a
workshop here next week.

00:36:09.970 --> 00:36:11.680
Maybe we'll do that.

00:36:11.680 --> 00:36:14.670
Make that list,
and look and see.

00:36:14.670 --> 00:36:17.920
Where can you weave in
a moment of mindfulness?

00:36:17.920 --> 00:36:19.570
I mean, be really specific--

00:36:19.570 --> 00:36:24.670
wake up, walk to the bathroom,
take my shower, make my tea,

00:36:24.670 --> 00:36:26.115
make lunch for my kids.

00:36:28.630 --> 00:36:33.580
Where can you weave in
a moment of mindfulness?

00:36:33.580 --> 00:36:35.110
Because it really is--

00:36:35.110 --> 00:36:38.180
we've heard this phrase--

00:36:38.180 --> 00:36:39.030
it's like exercise.

00:36:39.030 --> 00:36:41.320
It's like building a muscle.

00:36:41.320 --> 00:36:43.210
We have to build that
muscle, and so we

00:36:43.210 --> 00:36:45.752
have to practice over
and over and over again.

00:36:45.752 --> 00:36:47.710
One of my teachers gave
me a centering practice

00:36:47.710 --> 00:36:51.410
that I did 50, 60,
70, 80 times a day.

00:36:51.410 --> 00:36:54.190
Depending on what my day was
like, I would do it more.

00:36:54.190 --> 00:36:57.280
When my kids were very young, I
couldn't get away to a retreat.

00:36:57.280 --> 00:37:00.580
In fact, I thought I was
the biggest fraud meditation

00:37:00.580 --> 00:37:03.040
person, because I'd
never been on a retreat.

00:37:03.040 --> 00:37:06.040
And I was bemoaning this
to one of my teachers,

00:37:06.040 --> 00:37:08.980
and they really
stopped me in my tracks

00:37:08.980 --> 00:37:12.490
and said, no, Michelle,
this is the gift.

00:37:12.490 --> 00:37:14.530
This is what you're
going to get to share.

00:37:14.530 --> 00:37:18.160
And this is what we all need
to learn as parents, that just

00:37:18.160 --> 00:37:21.760
those moments, again
and again and again,

00:37:21.760 --> 00:37:24.024
cultivates an awakened life.

00:37:24.024 --> 00:37:25.190
And that's what we all want.

00:37:25.190 --> 00:37:26.929
We want to live awake.

00:37:26.929 --> 00:37:27.845
We want to be mindful.

00:37:33.820 --> 00:37:36.032
We can feel the joys.

00:37:36.032 --> 00:37:37.490
It's not just about,
I like to say,

00:37:37.490 --> 00:37:40.000
it's not just about the sadness,
and it's not just about, like,

00:37:40.000 --> 00:37:41.770
dealing with the
frustration and the pain

00:37:41.770 --> 00:37:44.560
and the anxiety, which
it's so wonderful for.

00:37:44.560 --> 00:37:46.100
That's what brought
me to practice.

00:37:46.100 --> 00:37:47.620
I have a lot of natural anxiety.

00:37:47.620 --> 00:37:49.870
I have it right now, and
it's not because I'm nervous.

00:37:49.870 --> 00:37:51.000
I have it most of the time.

00:37:51.000 --> 00:37:54.610
My chest is tight, my
belly is a little tight.

00:37:54.610 --> 00:37:57.190
I always kind of feel like I
can't breathe in all the way.

00:37:57.190 --> 00:37:58.532
I was just born that way.

00:37:58.532 --> 00:38:00.990
And that was one of the things
that brought me to practice.

00:38:00.990 --> 00:38:03.700
So it's wonderful
for those things.

00:38:03.700 --> 00:38:08.490
And we can experience
the joys even more.

00:38:08.490 --> 00:38:12.490
We can really smell the
scent of our baby's hair

00:38:12.490 --> 00:38:15.550
when they first get out of
the bath in the morning.

00:38:15.550 --> 00:38:18.460
We can watch them
play and see them

00:38:18.460 --> 00:38:23.320
learning new things as they
get older, and just be in awe.

00:38:23.320 --> 00:38:26.800
We want more moments of awe,
and practice brings us to awe.

00:38:30.290 --> 00:38:33.520
And it brings us
to a fierce heart.

00:38:33.520 --> 00:38:36.700
And here is what I think is
one of the most magical parts

00:38:36.700 --> 00:38:42.140
of practice for anyone, but
particularly for parents.

00:38:42.140 --> 00:38:45.110
Because our heart is going
to get broken over and over

00:38:45.110 --> 00:38:45.920
and over again.

00:38:45.920 --> 00:38:48.710
We're going to find
our lives and our heart

00:38:48.710 --> 00:38:50.270
on the floor in
a million pieces.

00:38:50.270 --> 00:38:52.180
And from those movies--

00:38:52.180 --> 00:38:54.500
those movies that
weren't working out.

00:38:54.500 --> 00:38:56.940
And we're going to
pick it up, and we're

00:38:56.940 --> 00:38:58.380
going to put it back together.

00:38:58.380 --> 00:39:01.560
And each time we put it back
together it gets stronger.

00:39:01.560 --> 00:39:03.480
And the question we
all have for ourselves

00:39:03.480 --> 00:39:09.520
is, can my heart remain
open when things are hard?

00:39:09.520 --> 00:39:12.370
Can I have that
fierce, open heart?

00:39:16.750 --> 00:39:19.000
And it's OK that it's cracked.

00:39:19.000 --> 00:39:22.360
And it's OK that
it's not perfect.

00:39:22.360 --> 00:39:26.250
We're not trying to
perfect ourselves.

00:39:26.250 --> 00:39:29.500
We're trying to
perfect our love.

00:39:29.500 --> 00:39:30.990
And I have a story
I'll read you.

00:39:30.990 --> 00:39:32.156
I think we have enough time.

00:39:35.750 --> 00:39:37.070
I love this story.

00:39:37.070 --> 00:39:40.700
The first time I heard
it was from Tara Brach.

00:39:40.700 --> 00:39:42.080
And it is from--

00:39:42.080 --> 00:39:44.090
it's written by Richard Selzer.

00:39:44.090 --> 00:39:47.150
It's from "Stories for the
Heart," compiled by Alice Gray.

00:39:47.150 --> 00:39:49.276
And it's called "The Kiss."

00:39:49.276 --> 00:39:52.340
"I stand by the bed
where a young woman lies,

00:39:52.340 --> 00:39:56.090
her face postoperative,
her mouth twisted in palsy,

00:39:56.090 --> 00:39:57.770
clownish.

00:39:57.770 --> 00:40:00.080
A tiny twig of the
facial nerve, the one

00:40:00.080 --> 00:40:03.200
to the muscles of her
mouth, has been severed.

00:40:03.200 --> 00:40:05.440
She will be thus from now on.

00:40:05.440 --> 00:40:08.340
Nevertheless, to remove
the tumor from her cheek,

00:40:08.340 --> 00:40:10.660
I had to cut the little nerve.

00:40:10.660 --> 00:40:13.120
Her young husband
is in the room.

00:40:13.120 --> 00:40:15.400
He stands on the
opposite side of the bed,

00:40:15.400 --> 00:40:19.390
and together they seem to
dwell in the evening lamplight,

00:40:19.390 --> 00:40:22.570
isolated from me, private.

00:40:22.570 --> 00:40:23.410
Who are they?

00:40:23.410 --> 00:40:27.760
I ask myself, he and this
wry mouth I have made,

00:40:27.760 --> 00:40:33.720
who gaze at each other and
touch each other so generously.

00:40:33.720 --> 00:40:36.650
'Will my mouth always
be like this?' she asks.

00:40:36.650 --> 00:40:38.630
'Yes,' I say. 'It will be.

00:40:38.630 --> 00:40:40.820
It is because the
nerve was cut.'

00:40:40.820 --> 00:40:44.960
She nods and is silent,
but the young man smiles.

00:40:44.960 --> 00:40:46.640
'I like it,' he says.

00:40:46.640 --> 00:40:48.930
'It's kind of cute.'

00:40:48.930 --> 00:40:51.390
All at once, I know who he is.

00:40:51.390 --> 00:40:54.240
I understand, and
I lower my gaze.

00:40:54.240 --> 00:40:58.620
One is not bold in an
encounter with God.

00:40:58.620 --> 00:41:01.580
Unmindful, he bends to
kiss her crooked mouth,

00:41:01.580 --> 00:41:04.380
and I am so close I
can see how he twists

00:41:04.380 --> 00:41:08.310
his own lips to accommodate
her, to show her

00:41:08.310 --> 00:41:11.940
that their kiss still works."

00:41:11.940 --> 00:41:14.040
So can we show
ourselves, and can we

00:41:14.040 --> 00:41:16.710
show our children
and our families over

00:41:16.710 --> 00:41:22.460
and over again, each
time we take a downturn,

00:41:22.460 --> 00:41:25.820
can we show them that
it all still works?

00:41:25.820 --> 00:41:30.110
So when the anger appears,
can we do that U-turn?

00:41:30.110 --> 00:41:33.320
Can we notice the
anger, have that pause?

00:41:33.320 --> 00:41:35.990
Can we do the U-turn,
and come in and explore?

00:41:35.990 --> 00:41:37.130
Can we get curious?

00:41:37.130 --> 00:41:39.020
What is this anger?

00:41:39.020 --> 00:41:40.020
Where is it coming from?

00:41:40.020 --> 00:41:41.100
What's it about?

00:41:41.100 --> 00:41:45.140
As soon-- you know curiosity
kills anger in a second.

00:41:45.140 --> 00:41:48.657
The second we get curious
about it, there's some space.

00:41:48.657 --> 00:41:50.240
And then we have the
opportunity to do

00:41:50.240 --> 00:41:51.906
something a little
more creative than we

00:41:51.906 --> 00:41:55.660
might have done otherwise.

00:41:55.660 --> 00:41:58.290
And when the fear
comes, we notice it,

00:41:58.290 --> 00:42:01.970
it arises, can we
stop, do the U-turn,

00:42:01.970 --> 00:42:06.130
and come in and
notice, ah, this fear.

00:42:06.130 --> 00:42:09.630
John Kabat-Zinn often
says, and this, too.

00:42:09.630 --> 00:42:10.260
And this, too.

00:42:10.260 --> 00:42:14.030
I can include all of this.

00:42:14.030 --> 00:42:16.640
And we get curious.

00:42:16.640 --> 00:42:19.810
And then the shame--

00:42:19.810 --> 00:42:25.000
can we do the U-turn and see
what is this about, this shame?

00:42:25.000 --> 00:42:25.860
Can I explore it?

00:42:25.860 --> 00:42:27.237
Can I understand it better?

00:42:30.210 --> 00:42:32.210
And then we give ourselves
some self-compassion.

00:42:32.210 --> 00:42:35.080
I'm a student of
Kristin Neff's work,

00:42:35.080 --> 00:42:36.890
if you haven't studied her.

00:42:36.890 --> 00:42:40.360
She was one of the original,
really the original researcher

00:42:40.360 --> 00:42:42.640
on self-compassion.

00:42:42.640 --> 00:42:46.690
And she shares that
what we need to do,

00:42:46.690 --> 00:42:50.440
when we're in these states of
really being hard on ourselves,

00:42:50.440 --> 00:42:55.000
is to be mindful, to bring up
our mindfulness, to realize

00:42:55.000 --> 00:42:57.822
that common humanity.

00:42:57.822 --> 00:42:58.780
We all go through this.

00:42:58.780 --> 00:43:00.530
Everyone in this room,
if you look around,

00:43:00.530 --> 00:43:04.550
we're all going through this
together, that it can be hard,

00:43:04.550 --> 00:43:06.850
and it can be beautiful,
and it can be miserable,

00:43:06.850 --> 00:43:09.930
and it can be fun.

00:43:09.930 --> 00:43:13.230
Common humanity-- this is
your tribe in this room.

00:43:13.230 --> 00:43:16.890
We're all connected
by being parents.

00:43:16.890 --> 00:43:18.360
And then being
kind to ourselves.

00:43:18.360 --> 00:43:20.250
And from the research
she says, always

00:43:20.250 --> 00:43:21.570
put your hand on your heart.

00:43:21.570 --> 00:43:23.700
So when I was doing that
little mirror exercise

00:43:23.700 --> 00:43:25.830
I tried, if I wasn't in
too strange of a place,

00:43:25.830 --> 00:43:28.710
to say something nice to
myself, put it on my heart,

00:43:28.710 --> 00:43:31.920
or just anywhere on my
body, just to touch myself.

00:43:31.920 --> 00:43:36.430
Let myself know, hm, a
little bit of kindness.

00:43:39.620 --> 00:43:42.090
This is reality for most
people in this room,

00:43:42.090 --> 00:43:44.960
for most people who are
listening on the live stream.

00:43:44.960 --> 00:43:46.580
This is the reality.

00:43:46.580 --> 00:43:47.925
This is how it's going to be.

00:43:47.925 --> 00:43:49.550
It's going to be up,
down, everything's

00:43:49.550 --> 00:43:52.370
fine, until it isn't,
then it is again.

00:43:52.370 --> 00:43:54.260
Mindful parenting
in a messy world--

00:43:54.260 --> 00:43:56.060
that's what we're living.

00:43:56.060 --> 00:44:01.820
And we can respond
more skillfully.

00:44:01.820 --> 00:44:03.800
That's what you hear
over and over again when

00:44:03.800 --> 00:44:05.180
you learn about mindfulness.

00:44:05.180 --> 00:44:07.100
It's all in the choice--

00:44:07.100 --> 00:44:10.840
moving from that, we
live this autopilot life,

00:44:10.840 --> 00:44:13.490
to get to choose, what
is my response going

00:44:13.490 --> 00:44:14.540
to be in this moment?

00:44:17.850 --> 00:44:21.840
So we can choose to go
down those dark places.

00:44:21.840 --> 00:44:23.880
And sometimes we are going
down the dark places.

00:44:23.880 --> 00:44:25.980
Last night, I was
kind of pooped.

00:44:25.980 --> 00:44:29.290
I'd been with my son for hours.

00:44:29.290 --> 00:44:31.320
And the compassion
just wasn't coming.

00:44:31.320 --> 00:44:34.680
And my husband brought the
light for a little while.

00:44:34.680 --> 00:44:37.590
I didn't have any
more light to give.

00:44:37.590 --> 00:44:39.270
And that's OK.

00:44:39.270 --> 00:44:40.500
That's OK.

00:44:40.500 --> 00:44:42.390
And we're blessed
if we have a partner

00:44:42.390 --> 00:44:44.880
that we can share that with--

00:44:44.880 --> 00:44:46.840
not everyone does.

00:44:46.840 --> 00:44:49.850
But we can go to
that side, or we

00:44:49.850 --> 00:44:53.910
can shine the light of awareness
on the fear, on the shame,

00:44:53.910 --> 00:44:56.850
on whatever is going on for us.

00:44:56.850 --> 00:44:59.290
And I don't always get it right.

00:44:59.290 --> 00:45:02.910
But these guys and these
faces keep me very motivated.

00:45:02.910 --> 00:45:05.040
And I'm sure you have your
own faces in your phone.

00:45:05.040 --> 00:45:07.840
I wish I could see all of them.

00:45:07.840 --> 00:45:09.810
But this is why we practice.

00:45:09.810 --> 00:45:12.606
We practice for ourselves,
we practice for the world,

00:45:12.606 --> 00:45:13.980
and we practice
for our families.

00:45:13.980 --> 00:45:18.600
And they are-- they will
bring us to our knees

00:45:18.600 --> 00:45:20.790
in spiritual practice--
our children.

00:45:20.790 --> 00:45:26.170
They will trigger every
undealt-with issue

00:45:26.170 --> 00:45:28.500
from childhood we have.

00:45:28.500 --> 00:45:31.140
And that's also
their gift to us,

00:45:31.140 --> 00:45:32.790
because they point
us to our freedom.

00:45:32.790 --> 00:45:35.820
They point us to where
the work needs to happen.

00:45:35.820 --> 00:45:38.730
And I am very grateful to be
on this path with all of you

00:45:38.730 --> 00:45:41.270
in this room and
everyone listening.

00:45:41.270 --> 00:45:41.770
Thank you.

00:45:44.303 --> 00:45:45.594
SPEAKER 1: Thank you, Michelle.

00:45:45.594 --> 00:45:47.810
So we'll take questions.

00:45:47.810 --> 00:45:50.550
Anyone have a
question in the room?

00:45:53.070 --> 00:45:54.820
AUDIENCE: Hi, I'm
[INAUDIBLE] from Brazil.

00:45:54.820 --> 00:46:00.710
I'm very glad that I'm here,
just to get your talk here--

00:46:00.710 --> 00:46:01.830
MICHELLE GALE: Thank you.

00:46:01.830 --> 00:46:03.550
AUDIENCE: --at the same moment.

00:46:03.550 --> 00:46:05.580
So my point is about emotions.

00:46:05.580 --> 00:46:10.500
How you call or you teach
somehow about emotions

00:46:10.500 --> 00:46:11.650
for your children?

00:46:11.650 --> 00:46:13.230
MICHELLE GALE: How do you
teach them about emotions?

00:46:13.230 --> 00:46:14.900
AUDIENCE: Yeah,
emotional intelligence.

00:46:14.900 --> 00:46:18.381
But not this kind of approach--
a more natural approach

00:46:18.381 --> 00:46:18.880
for this.

00:46:18.880 --> 00:46:19.713
MICHELLE GALE: Yeah.

00:46:21.900 --> 00:46:26.340
Well, one idea that I share with
my kids is naming the emotion.

00:46:26.340 --> 00:46:28.350
And there's some wonderful
research on this.

00:46:28.350 --> 00:46:32.790
Matthew Lieberman, I think, in
2014 talked about just naming

00:46:32.790 --> 00:46:35.730
the emotion, how that clears
the prefrontal cortex,

00:46:35.730 --> 00:46:37.240
calms the amygdala.

00:46:37.240 --> 00:46:39.380
So you teach them
just to name it.

00:46:39.380 --> 00:46:42.360
And I think that's in a lot of
the parenting literature now.

00:46:42.360 --> 00:46:43.740
Oh, you're angry.

00:46:43.740 --> 00:46:45.030
Oh, you feel sad.

00:46:45.030 --> 00:46:47.880
And it might seem a
little hokey to do that.

00:46:47.880 --> 00:46:50.310
We do it more often
when they're young.

00:46:50.310 --> 00:46:53.280
But we can also inquire with
them when they're older,

00:46:53.280 --> 00:46:54.940
like, what is the emotion?

00:46:54.940 --> 00:46:57.030
And if you can,
depending on your child--

00:46:57.030 --> 00:46:59.310
my kids are kind
of used to it now.

00:46:59.310 --> 00:47:00.890
Where is it in your body?

00:47:00.890 --> 00:47:01.860
Locate it.

00:47:01.860 --> 00:47:03.540
Is there a color?

00:47:03.540 --> 00:47:04.890
What does it feel like?

00:47:04.890 --> 00:47:08.670
So what we want is for them
to get to know their emotions,

00:47:08.670 --> 00:47:10.800
and the body is where they live.

00:47:10.800 --> 00:47:13.740
We experience them in
the body long before they

00:47:13.740 --> 00:47:15.750
come into cognition.

00:47:15.750 --> 00:47:18.120
And another little trick
with emotions that I also

00:47:18.120 --> 00:47:21.960
like to share is time them.

00:47:21.960 --> 00:47:24.705
So when they were really little
and they'd say, I'm so angry,

00:47:24.705 --> 00:47:27.870
I'm like, wow,
you're really angry.

00:47:27.870 --> 00:47:29.460
Let's see how long it lasts.

00:47:29.460 --> 00:47:31.840
How long can you be angry?

00:47:31.840 --> 00:47:33.330
And put on the timer.

00:47:33.330 --> 00:47:34.830
Let's see how long
you can be angry.

00:47:34.830 --> 00:47:35.954
And now it's a game, right?

00:47:35.954 --> 00:47:38.097
So now it'll pass quickly.

00:47:38.097 --> 00:47:40.180
Because now they want to
see how long it can pass.

00:47:40.180 --> 00:47:44.430
But within 60 seconds
or a minute, it's gone.

00:47:44.430 --> 00:47:45.990
And so they see, oh.

00:47:45.990 --> 00:47:50.140
So what we're teaching them
is, it comes, and it goes.

00:47:50.140 --> 00:47:51.570
It begins, and it ends.

00:47:51.570 --> 00:47:53.673
Have you ever been
angry all day?

00:47:53.673 --> 00:47:54.540
I'll ask them.

00:47:54.540 --> 00:47:56.130
Well, no, not really.

00:47:56.130 --> 00:47:57.840
It's usually not that way.

00:47:57.840 --> 00:47:59.075
It's usually not that way.

00:47:59.075 --> 00:48:01.086
Is that helpful?

00:48:01.086 --> 00:48:02.260
Anybody else?

00:48:02.260 --> 00:48:03.510
SPEAKER 1: Hold on one second.

00:48:03.510 --> 00:48:04.442
Let me get the mic.

00:48:07.697 --> 00:48:08.530
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:48:08.530 --> 00:48:10.140
Thank you for being here
and sharing your stories.

00:48:10.140 --> 00:48:12.160
So quick question--
like you mentioned,

00:48:12.160 --> 00:48:14.657
there is this
structured practice

00:48:14.657 --> 00:48:16.240
that you sit and
meditate, and there's

00:48:16.240 --> 00:48:17.909
being mindful during
the day, and then

00:48:17.909 --> 00:48:19.450
you mentioned a lot
of different ways

00:48:19.450 --> 00:48:21.400
how to teach the latter one.

00:48:21.400 --> 00:48:24.480
Have you tried to do like a
structured practice, meaning,

00:48:24.480 --> 00:48:27.070
let's sit down together
and have a meditation

00:48:27.070 --> 00:48:28.150
session with your kids?

00:48:28.150 --> 00:48:28.750
MICHELLE GALE: With my kids.

00:48:28.750 --> 00:48:29.333
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:48:29.333 --> 00:48:32.260
MICHELLE GALE: Well, the way
I came to teaching meditation

00:48:32.260 --> 00:48:35.350
was actually, I went through
the Mindful Schools program,

00:48:35.350 --> 00:48:37.780
because I wanted to teach
it to my kids at home.

00:48:37.780 --> 00:48:40.452
And I ended up teaching
in their school.

00:48:40.452 --> 00:48:42.910
So I taught in their school as
a volunteer for three years.

00:48:42.910 --> 00:48:45.040
So they got it from me there.

00:48:45.040 --> 00:48:48.010
And I found, at least
for me, anyway, at home,

00:48:48.010 --> 00:48:53.650
to actually try to explicitly
teach it, most kids won't.

00:48:53.650 --> 00:48:54.640
Most kids won't.

00:48:54.640 --> 00:48:56.290
But I let them see me.

00:48:56.290 --> 00:48:58.720
So if they come in my
room and I'm sitting--

00:48:58.720 --> 00:49:00.850
I love, Jon Kabat-Zinn
tells this story

00:49:00.850 --> 00:49:03.960
of his son Will Kabat-Zinn
is a mindfulness teacher

00:49:03.960 --> 00:49:06.860
in his own right at Spirit
Rock and all around.

00:49:06.860 --> 00:49:09.550
And he would say
he'd be sitting--

00:49:09.550 --> 00:49:11.620
Jon got up very early to
sit, 4:00 in the morning

00:49:11.620 --> 00:49:12.280
all the time.

00:49:12.280 --> 00:49:14.680
You know, did his whole
yoga and meditation

00:49:14.680 --> 00:49:18.182
and he says he never ever asked
his kids to sit in meditation.

00:49:18.182 --> 00:49:20.140
But they'd come in, and
they'd see him sitting.

00:49:20.140 --> 00:49:21.723
And he'd have a
blanket around, and he

00:49:21.723 --> 00:49:24.696
said he'd open the blanket,
and they'd come in,

00:49:24.696 --> 00:49:25.820
and he'd close the blanket.

00:49:25.820 --> 00:49:28.480
And that image to
me is so beautiful.

00:49:28.480 --> 00:49:31.480
And then they'd just sit
there with him in meditation.

00:49:31.480 --> 00:49:34.900
So depending on your child,
some kids will eat it up.

00:49:34.900 --> 00:49:36.634
Books are a really great way.

00:49:36.634 --> 00:49:37.300
There's so many.

00:49:37.300 --> 00:49:40.340
"Moody Cow Meditates"
I think it's called.

00:49:40.340 --> 00:49:41.830
And I mean, there's
a whole bunch

00:49:41.830 --> 00:49:44.470
of beautiful children's books.

00:49:44.470 --> 00:49:46.990
And so reading-- we
did a lot of reading.

00:49:46.990 --> 00:49:49.900
But explicit teaching, I
think it's the weaving in.

00:49:49.900 --> 00:49:51.100
I think it's in the pausing.

00:49:51.100 --> 00:49:53.935
Before my kids used to go to
school when they were younger,

00:49:53.935 --> 00:49:55.060
they started walking alone.

00:49:55.060 --> 00:49:56.143
And I was all freaked out.

00:49:56.143 --> 00:49:58.990
I'm like, it's so weird,
they're leaving without me

00:49:58.990 --> 00:50:01.460
and I don't like it.

00:50:01.460 --> 00:50:03.460
And so for me, this was
a me-practice, I'm like,

00:50:03.460 --> 00:50:05.490
would you guys be willing
to just hold hands?

00:50:05.490 --> 00:50:07.150
You know, do our little
circle like we do at dinner,

00:50:07.150 --> 00:50:09.400
and do a little hand
squeeze and take one breath?

00:50:09.400 --> 00:50:10.210
Like, OK.

00:50:10.210 --> 00:50:12.100
You know, they were
willing to do it.

00:50:12.100 --> 00:50:14.380
And then, if I forgot,
they would ask for it.

00:50:14.380 --> 00:50:16.480
So that probably went on
for three or four months.

00:50:16.480 --> 00:50:19.090
Every morning before they
left for school, one breath.

00:50:19.090 --> 00:50:21.280
So my encouragement
is to weave it in.

00:50:21.280 --> 00:50:24.100
And if you have a child that
is really excited to learn,

00:50:24.100 --> 00:50:25.540
then go for it.

00:50:25.540 --> 00:50:26.314
Yeah.

00:50:26.314 --> 00:50:27.480
AUDIENCE: I have a question.

00:50:27.480 --> 00:50:28.313
MICHELLE GALE: Yeah.

00:50:28.313 --> 00:50:31.267
AUDIENCE: So tantrums--
what's the mindful response?

00:50:31.267 --> 00:50:33.100
What would be a best
practice if you've just

00:50:33.100 --> 00:50:36.737
got someone who's tantruming
a lot, or big time?

00:50:36.737 --> 00:50:37.570
MICHELLE GALE: Yeah.

00:50:37.570 --> 00:50:39.550
Well, I think there's
a few layers to that.

00:50:39.550 --> 00:50:41.466
There's always like,
what's under the tantrum?

00:50:41.466 --> 00:50:43.960
So that's always where, from
a mindfulness perspective,

00:50:43.960 --> 00:50:44.620
where--

00:50:44.620 --> 00:50:46.450
it's never the behavior.

00:50:46.450 --> 00:50:48.796
It's always there's
some emotional reaction.

00:50:48.796 --> 00:50:50.170
And what is the
emotion, and what

00:50:50.170 --> 00:50:53.350
is-- nonviolent communication,
very nonviolent communication.

00:50:53.350 --> 00:50:55.360
What's the need
that's not being met?

00:50:55.360 --> 00:50:57.820
And I love-- I think
Dan Segal does HALT--

00:50:57.820 --> 00:51:03.510
hungry, HALT angry,
lonely, tired.

00:51:03.510 --> 00:51:07.020
You know, you can ask yourself--
hungry, angry, lonely, tired?

00:51:07.020 --> 00:51:09.180
So to know what's under
it, what's causing it.

00:51:09.180 --> 00:51:11.120
And if you can get them
to share, wonderful.

00:51:11.120 --> 00:51:13.119
Sometimes in the middle
of a tantrum not always.

00:51:13.119 --> 00:51:15.870
But then it's being able, like I
was saying earlier, to hold it,

00:51:15.870 --> 00:51:18.710
so they know I can
hold this with you.

00:51:18.710 --> 00:51:20.310
You're not alone in this.

00:51:20.310 --> 00:51:21.900
We can be in this together.

00:51:21.900 --> 00:51:23.610
And just that alone--

00:51:23.610 --> 00:51:26.567
trying to stop it is,
unless, you know, sometimes

00:51:26.567 --> 00:51:27.900
you're in the middle of a store.

00:51:27.900 --> 00:51:30.500
And you're like, how
about a Twizzler?

00:51:30.500 --> 00:51:31.125
And that works.

00:51:31.125 --> 00:51:33.480
And that's just-- sometimes
it's just survival.

00:51:33.480 --> 00:51:36.794
But if you've got space
and time, hold it.

00:51:36.794 --> 00:51:37.460
AUDIENCE: Great.

00:51:37.460 --> 00:51:38.544
Well, thank you so much.

00:51:38.544 --> 00:51:39.460
I think we're at time.

00:51:39.460 --> 00:51:40.730
Thank you so much, Michelle.

00:51:40.730 --> 00:51:42.580
MICHELLE GALE: Thank you.

